  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "Oil painting on canvas (98.1 × 120.1 cm, signed and dated 1838) by Dutch painter **Nicolaas Pieneman** (1809–1860). The painting depicts the immediate aftermath of the assassination attempt on William I, Prince of Orange (\"William the Silent\") by **Juan de Jáuregui** in Antwerp on 18 March 1582. The scene shows the wounded Willem I in a chair, his wife Charlotte of Bourbon attending him, the dead body of Jáuregui on the floor, and the young **Prince Maurits** (age 14–15) directing soldiers to examine the assassin's corpse. A 19th-century Dutch nationalist history painting acquired by Teylers in or around 1838 — the year the museum's First Painting Gallery opened. A steel engraving after this painting was made by Johann Wilhelm Kaiser (I) in 1853–54 for the *Vereeniging ter Bevordering van Beeldende Kunsten* (Teylers KG 08154).",
